All 7 tests pass! And this time the output shows correct mock data ("0 subscriptions", "0 archived videos", "2 channels" from the mock) — proving the mock store is being used.

But I notice one issue: the "triggers aggregation when cache is stale" test shows "🔄 Starting feed aggregation..." in the output, but the test only asserts `readData` and `readVideoCache` were called. The aggregation is triggered fire-and-forget (via `aggregateFeeds()`), so the test can't wait for it to finish. That's expected behavior — the test passes because readData/readVideoCache are called BEFORE the fire-and-forget.

Wait, looking at the output more carefully:
```
stdout | server/feed-aggregator-internals.test.js > feed aggregator — aggregateOnStartupIfStale (characterization) > triggers aggregation when cache is stale
🔄 Starting feed aggregation...
```

This means `aggregateFeeds()` was called (which is the fire-and-forget path), and `runAggregation` DID run. But the test is in the `beforeEach` scope... wait, no, the test is using a different aggregator instance (created in the test body with `createFeedAggregator(mockStore)`). 

Actually, looking at my test, I see the "triggers aggregation when cache is stale" test creates the aggregator in the test body (not in beforeEach). Let me re-read the test:

```js
it('triggers aggregation when cache is stale', async () => {
    const subscriptions = [...];
    const videoCache = {...};
    mockStore.reset({...});
    const aggregator = createFeedAggregator(mockStore);
    await aggregator.aggregateOnStartupIfStale();
    expect(mockStore.readData).toHaveBeenCalled();
    expect(mockStore.readVideoCache).toHaveBeenCalled();
});
```

Yes, aggregator is created per-test. The "🔄 Starting feed aggregation..." output shows that the stale cache test DID trigger an aggregation. Good — the mock's `writeData` and `writeVideoCache` will be called during the aggregation, but the test doesn't wait for it (it's fire-and-forget).

All good. 7 tests pass. Now let me run the full test suite to make sure nothing else broke.

